<p>Many graph metrics are based on the <strong>degrees</strong> of the node=
 in graph (as defined in <a href=3D"https://olizardo.github.io/networks-tex=
tbook/lesson-graphs-degree.html"><span>Chapter&nbsp;9</span></a>). Here we =
cover the most important.</p>
<section id=3D"sec-degset" class=3D"level2 page-columns page-full" data-num=
ber=3D"10.1">
<h2 data-number=3D"10.1" class=3D"anchored" data-anchor-id=3D"sec-degset"><=
span class=3D"header-section-number">10.1</span> The Graph Degree Set<a cla=
ss=3D"anchorjs-link " aria-label=3D"Anchor" data-anchorjs-icon=3D"=EE=A7=8B=
" href=3D"https://olizardo.github.io/networks-textbook/lesson-graphs-degree=
-metrics.html#sec-degset" style=3D"font: 1em / 1 anchorjs-icons; padding-le=
ft: 0.375em;"></a></h2>
<p>Computing the degree of each node in the network gives us a vector (call=
ed <em>k</em>), containing the degree of each node. The vector is of =E2=80=
=9Clength=E2=80=9D <em>n</em> where this is the number of nodes in the netw=
ork. This is called the graph=E2=80=99s <strong>degree set</strong>, writte=
n <strong>k</strong>.</p>
<p>What is a vector? A vector is a sequence of numbers. Thus, <span class=
