 1em / 1 anchorjs-icons; padding-left: 0.375em;"></a></h2>
<p>When we list the members of the degree set (each node=E2=80=99s degree) =
in decreasing order from bigger to smaller, this is called the graph=E2=80=
=99s <strong>degree sequence</strong>, and it is written <strong>d</strong>=
. Every graph has its own degree sequence, but graphs with very different s=
tructure (in terms of other graph metrics) can have the same degree sequenc=
e <span class=3D"citation" data-cites=3D"kim_etal09">(<a href=3D"https://ol=
izardo.github.io/networks-textbook/lesson-graphs-degree-metrics.html#ref-ki=
m_etal09" role=3D"doc-biblioref" aria-expanded=3D"false">Kim et al. 2009</a=
>)</span>.</p>
