<section id=3D"sec-degsum" class=3D"level2" data-number=3D"10.5">
<h2 data-number=3D"10.5" class=3D"anchored" data-anchor-id=3D"sec-degsum"><=
span class=3D"header-section-number">10.5</span> The Sum of Degrees<a class=
=3D"anchorjs-link " aria-label=3D"Anchor" data-anchorjs-icon=3D"=EE=A7=8B" =
href=3D"https://olizardo.github.io/networks-textbook/lesson-graphs-degree-m=
etrics.html#sec-degsum" style=3D"font: 1em / 1 anchorjs-icons; padding-left=
: 0.375em;"></a></h2>
<p>Note that if we know the degree set of an undirected graph, we can figur=
e out how many total edges there are in the graph. The reason for this is t=
hat the degree of each node can be defined in terms of the total number of =
edges incident on the node (as we noted earlier). So that means that if we =
know each node=E2=80=99s degree, then we can also know how many total edges=
 there are in the graph.</p>
<p>The first step we need to do is compute the <strong>sum of degrees</stro=
ng> of each node in the graph. This quantity is written <span class=3D"math=
 inline"><mjx-container class=3D"MathJax CtxtMenu_Attached_0" jax=3D"CHTML"=
 tabindex=3D"0" ctxtmenu_counter=3D"20" style=3D"font-size: 119.6%; positio=
n: relative;"><mjx-math class=3D"MJX-TEX" aria-hidden=3D"true"><mjx-munder =
limits=3D"false"><mjx-mo class=3D"mjx-sop"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c2211 TEX-S1=
"></mjx-c></mjx-mo><mjx-script style=3D"vertical-align: -0.285em;"><mjx-mi =
class=3D"mjx-i" size=3D"s"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c1D456 TEX-I"></mjx-c></mjx-=
mi></mjx-script></mjx-munder><mjx-msub space=3D"2"><mjx-mi class=3D"mjx-i">=
<mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c1D458 TEX-I"></mjx-c></mjx-mi><mjx-script style=3D"ver=
tical-align: -0.15em;"><mjx-mi class=3D"mjx-i" size=3D"s"><mjx-c class=3D"m=
jx-c1D456 TEX-I"></mjx-c></mjx-mi></mjx-script></mjx-msub></mjx-math><mjx-a=
ssistive-mml unselectable=3D"on" display=3D"inline"><math xmlns=3D"http://w=
ww.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><munder><mo data-mjx-texclass=3D"OP">=E2=88=91<=
/mo><mi>i</mi></munder><msub><mi>k</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></math></mjx-assist=
ive-mml></mjx-container></span>. For the degree set of the graph shown in <=
a href=3D"https://olizardo.github.io/networks-textbook/lesson-graphs-degree=
-metrics.html#fig-degree">Figure&nbsp;<span>10.1</span></a>, we can see tha=
t the sum of the degrees <span class=3D"math inline"><mjx-container class=
=3D"MathJax CtxtMenu_Attached_0" jax=3D"CHTML" tabindex=3D"0" ctxtmenu_coun=
ter=3D"21" style=3D"font-size: 119.6%; position: relative;"><mjx-math class=
=3D"MJX-TEX" aria-hidden=3D"true"><mjx-munder limits=3D"false"><mjx-mo clas=
s=3D"mjx-sop"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c2211 TEX-S1"></mjx-c></mjx-mo><mjx-scrip=
t style=3D"vertical-align: -0.285em;"><mjx-mi class=3D"mjx-i" size=3D"s"><m=
jx-c class=3D"mjx-c1D456 TEX-I"></mjx-c></mjx-mi></mjx-script></mjx-munder>=
<mjx-msub space=3D"2"><mjx-mi class=3D"mjx-i"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c1D458 TE=
X-I"></mjx-c></mjx-mi><mjx-script style=3D"vertical-align: -0.15em;"><mjx-m=
i class=3D"mjx-i" size=3D"s"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c1D456 TEX-I"></mjx-c></mj=
x-mi></mjx-script></mjx-msub><mjx-mo class=3D"mjx-n" space=3D"4"><mjx-c cla=
ss=3D"mjx-c3D"></mjx-c></mjx-mo><mjx-mn class=3D"mjx-n" space=3D"4"><mjx-c =
class=3D"mjx-c33"></mjx-c><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c32"></mjx-c></mjx-mn></mjx-m=
ath><mjx-assistive-mml unselectable=3D"on" display=3D"inline"><math xmlns=
=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><munder><mo data-mjx-texclass=3D"OP=
">=E2=88=91</mo><mi>i</mi></munder><msub><mi>k</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>=3D=
</mo><mn>32</mn></math></mjx-assistive-mml></mjx-container></span> (go ahea=
d use a calculator to add up all the numbers in <a href=3D"https://olizardo=
.github.io/networks-textbook/lesson-graphs-degree-metrics.html#tbl-degset">=
Table&nbsp;<span>10.1</span></a>).</p>
<p>If you go back to the graph shown in <a href=3D"https://olizardo.github.=
io/networks-textbook/lesson-graphs-degree-metrics.html#fig-degree">Figure&n=
bsp;<span>10.1</span></a> and count the number of lines, you can see that t=
here are 16. So summing up the degrees of each node ended up totaling <em>t=
wice</em> the number of edges shown in the graph: <span class=3D"math inlin=
e"><mjx-container class=3D"MathJax CtxtMenu_Attached_0" jax=3D"CHTML" tabin=
dex=3D"0" ctxtmenu_counter=3D"22" style=3D"font-size: 119.6%; position: rel=
ative;"><mjx-math class=3D"MJX-TEX" aria-hidden=3D"true"><mjx-mn class=3D"m=
jx-n"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c31"></mjx-c><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c36"></mjx-c></m=
jx-mn><mjx-mo class=3D"mjx-n" space=3D"3"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-cD7"></mjx-c>=
</mjx-mo><mjx-mn class=3D"mjx-n" space=3D"3"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c32"></mjx=
-c></mjx-mn><mjx-mo class=3D"mjx-n" space=3D"4"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c3D"></=
mjx-c></mjx-mo><mjx-mn class=3D"mjx-n" space=3D"4"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c33"=
></mjx-c><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c32"></mjx-c></mjx-mn></mjx-math><mjx-assistiv=
e-mml unselectable=3D"on" display=3D"inline"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.o=
rg/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>16</mn><mo>=C3=97</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=3D</mo><mn>32=
</mn></math></mjx-assistive-mml></mjx-container></span>. The reason for thi=
s is that each edge is incident (touches) two nodes, so it makes sense that=
 when you add up the degrees of each node you end up with twice the amount =
of lines shown in the visual representation of the graph.</p>
<p>So the relationship between the sum of the degrees and the number of edg=
es in an undirected graph is one of simple doubling. In equation form, this=
 is written:</p>
<p><span id=3D"eq-sumki"><span class=3D"math display"><mjx-container class=
=3D"MathJax CtxtMenu_Attached_0" jax=3D"CHTML" display=3D"true" width=3D"fu=
ll" tabindex=3D"0" ctxtmenu_counter=3D"23" style=3D"font-size: 119.6%; min-=
width: 11.882em; position: relative;"><mjx-math width=3D"full" display=3D"t=
rue" class=3D"MJX-TEX" aria-hidden=3D"true"><mjx-mtable width=3D"full" side=
=3D"right" style=3D"min-width: 11.882em;"><mjx-table style=3D"width: auto; =
min-width: 5.17em; margin: 0px 3.356em;"><mjx-itable width=3D"full"><mjx-ml=
abeledtr><mjx-mtd><mjx-munder><mjx-row><mjx-base><mjx-mo class=3D"mjx-lop">=
<mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c2211 TEX-S2"></mjx-c></mjx-mo></mjx-base></mjx-row><mj=
x-row><mjx-under style=3D"padding-top: 0.167em; padding-left: 0.6em;"><mjx-=
mi class=3D"mjx-i" size=3D"s"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c1D456 TEX-I"></mjx-c></m=
jx-mi></mjx-under></mjx-row></mjx-munder><mjx-msub space=3D"2"><mjx-mi clas=
s=3D"mjx-i"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c1D458 TEX-I"></mjx-c></mjx-mi><mjx-script =
style=3D"vertical-align: -0.15em;"><mjx-mi class=3D"mjx-i" size=3D"s"><mjx-=
c class=3D"mjx-c1D456 TEX-I"></mjx-c></mjx-mi></mjx-script></mjx-msub><mjx-=
mo class=3D"mjx-n" space=3D"4"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c3D"></mjx-c></mjx-mo><m=
jx-mn class=3D"mjx-n" space=3D"4"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c32"></mjx-c></mjx-mn=
><mjx-mi class=3D"mjx-i"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c1D45A TEX-I"></mjx-c></mjx-mi=
><mjx-tstrut></mjx-tstrut></mjx-mtd></mjx-mlabeledtr></mjx-itable></mjx-tab=
le><mjx-labels style=3D"width: 11.882em;"><mjx-itable align=3D"right" style=
=3D"right: 0px;"><mjx-mtr style=3D"height: 2.142em;"><mjx-mtd id=3D"mjx-eqn=
:10.4"><mjx-mtext class=3D"mjx-n"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c28"></mjx-c><mjx-c c=
lass=3D"mjx-c31"></mjx-c><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c30"></mjx-c><mjx-c class=3D"m=
jx-c2E"></mjx-c><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c34"></mjx-c><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c29"><=
/mjx-c></mjx-mtext><mjx-tstrut style=3D"height: 2.142em; vertical-align: -1=
.192em;"></mjx-tstrut></mjx-mtd></mjx-mtr></mjx-itable></mjx-labels></mjx-m=
table></mjx-math><mjx-assistive-mml unselectable=3D"on" display=3D"block"><=
math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display=3D"block"><mtable=
 displaystyle=3D"true"><mlabeledtr><mtd><mtext>(10.4)</mtext></mtd><mtd><mu=
nder><mo data-mjx-texclass=3D"OP">=E2=88=91</mo><mi>i</mi></munder><msub><m=
i>k</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>=3D</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>m</mi></mtd></mlabeledtr=
></mtable></math></mjx-assistive-mml></mjx-container></span></span></p>
<p>Where <em>m</em> is the cardinality of the graph=E2=80=99s edge set <spa=
n class=3D"math inline"><mjx-container class=3D"MathJax CtxtMenu_Attached_0=
" jax=3D"CHTML" tabindex=3D"0" ctxtmenu_counter=3D"24" style=3D"font-size: =
119.6%; position: relative;"><mjx-math class=3D"MJX-TEX" aria-hidden=3D"tru=
e"><mjx-mo class=3D"mjx-n"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c7C"></mjx-c></mjx-mo><mjx-m=
i class=3D"mjx-i"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c1D438 TEX-I"></mjx-c></mjx-mi><mjx-m=
o class=3D"mjx-n"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c7C"></mjx-c></mjx-mo></mjx-math><mjx=
-assistive-mml unselectable=3D"on" display=3D"inline"><math xmlns=3D"http:/=
/www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo data-mjx-texclass=3D"ORD" stretchy=3D"fal=
se">|</mo><mi>E</mi><mo data-mjx-texclass=3D"ORD" stretchy=3D"false">|</mo>=
</math></mjx-assistive-mml></mjx-container></span>. Some people call this <=
strong>the first theorem of graph theory</strong> <span class=3D"citation" =
data-cites=3D"benjamin15">(<a href=3D"https://olizardo.github.io/networks-t=
extbook/lesson-graphs-degree-metrics.html#ref-benjamin15" role=3D"doc-bibli=
oref" aria-expanded=3D"false">Benjamin, Chartrand, and Zhang 2015, 20</a>)<=
/span>!</p>
<p>Another way to think about why we end up with twice the number of edges,=
 is that in an undirected graph <span class=3D"math inline"><mjx-container =
class=3D"MathJax CtxtMenu_Attached_0" jax=3D"CHTML" tabindex=3D"0" ctxtmenu=
_counter=3D"25" style=3D"font-size: 119.6%; position: relative;"><mjx-math =
class=3D"MJX-TEX" aria-hidden=3D"true"><mjx-mi class=3D"mjx-i"><mjx-c class=
=3D"mjx-c1D43A TEX-I"></mjx-c></mjx-mi></mjx-math><mjx-assistive-mml unsele=
ctable=3D"on" display=3D"inline"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math=
/MathML"><mi>G</mi></math></mjx-assistive-mml></mjx-container></span>, if n=
ode <em>A</em> is a member of the set of neighbors of node <em>B</em>, then=
 node <em>B</em> is necessarily also a member of the set of neighbors of no=
de <em>A</em>. Thus, when computing the degree of each node, the edge <em>A=
B</em> does double duty, counting for the computation of both node <em>A</e=
m> and node <em>B</em>=E2=80=99s degree scores, when we sum the degrees the=
 edge thus shows up twice. Note that in the directed case we don=E2=80=99t =
have that problem, in which case <span class=3D"math inline"><mjx-container=
 class=3D"MathJax CtxtMenu_Attached_0" jax=3D"CHTML" tabindex=3D"0" ctxtmen=
u_counter=3D"26" style=3D"font-size: 119.6%; position: relative;"><mjx-math=
 class=3D"MJX-TEX" aria-hidden=3D"true"><mjx-munder limits=3D"false"><mjx-m=
o class=3D"mjx-sop"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c2211 TEX-S1"></mjx-c></mjx-mo><mjx=
-script style=3D"vertical-align: -0.285em;"><mjx-mi class=3D"mjx-i" size=3D=
"s"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c1D456 TEX-I"></mjx-c></mjx-mi></mjx-script></mjx-m=
under><mjx-msub space=3D"2"><mjx-mi class=3D"mjx-i"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c1D=
458 TEX-I"></mjx-c></mjx-mi><mjx-script style=3D"vertical-align: -0.15em;">=
<mjx-mi class=3D"mjx-i" size=3D"s"><mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c1D456 TEX-I"></mjx-=
c></mjx-mi></mjx-script></mjx-msub><mjx-mo class=3D"mjx-n" space=3D"4"><mjx=
-c class=3D"mjx-c3D"></mjx-c></mjx-mo><mjx-mi class=3D"mjx-i" space=3D"4"><=
mjx-c class=3D"mjx-c1D45A TEX-I"></mjx-c></mjx-mi></mjx-math><mjx-assistive=
-mml unselectable=3D"on" display=3D"inline"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.or=
g/1998/Math/MathML"><munder><mo data-mjx-texclass=3D"OP">=E2=88=91</mo><mi>=
i</mi></munder><msub><mi>k</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>=3D</mo><mi>m</mi></mat=
h></mjx-assistive-mml></mjx-container></span>.</p>
</section>
