ptions (e.g., regular graphs), <em>the average number of friends of the typ=
ical person</em> (the graph=E2=80=99s average degree) is <strong>smaller</s=
trong> than the <em>average number of friends of friends of the typical per=
son in the same social network</em> (the graph=E2=80=99s average nearest ne=
ighbor degree). That is, <strong>your friends have more friends than you do=
</strong>. Don=E2=80=99t get depressed. This is just how social networks wo=
rk.</p>
